ion-outlook-us-economy-job-market-unemployment-soft-landing-citi-2024-2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egone%20away%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20it's%20unclear%20if%20the%20US%20will%20experience%20a%20recession%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Feconomic-recession-outlook-downturn-fears-pushed-2025-after-ism-data-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Enear%20future%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20data%20from%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Ethe%20National%20Bureau%20of%20Economic%20Research%20(NBER)%3Cstrong%3E%20%E2%80%94%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20the%20private%2C%20nonprofit%20research%20group%20that's%20responsible%20for%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fafrica.businessinsider.com%2Ffinance%2Fwhat-is-a-recession-how-economists-define-periods-of-economic-downturn%2F89zb8f0%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etracking%20the%20start%20and%20end%20dates%20of%20US%20recessions%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20shows%20a%20promising%20trend%3A%20Recessions%20have%20become%20less%20common%20in%20the%20US.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBetween%201990%20and%202023%2C%20the%20US%20economy%20spent%2036%20months%20in%20a%20recession%2C%20with%20the%20most%20recent%20US%20recession%20in%202020%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcoronavirus-recession-lasted-2-months-shortest-downturn-us-history-nber-2021-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Elasting%20two%20months%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20NBER%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nber.org%2Fresearch%2Fbusiness-cycle-dating%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edefines%3C%2Fa%3E%20a%20recession%20as%20the%20period%20between%20a%20peak%20of%20economic%20activity%20and%20its%20lowest%20point%20%E2%80%94%20the%20period%20typically%20must%20include%20a%20%26quot%3Bsignificant%20decline%20in%20economic%20activity%26quot%3B%20that%20lasts%20more%20than%20a%20few%20months.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBetween%201960%20and%201989%2C%20the%20economy%20spent%2059%20months%20in%20a%20recession.%20The%20further%20back%20you%20go%20%E2%80%94%20the%20NBER%20data%20goes%20to%20about%201850%20%E2%80%94%20the%20more%20common%20recessions%20were.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-script%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20data-styles%3D%5C%22default-width%5C%22%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22custom%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2F2L5dv%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Months%20of%20US%20recessions%20in%20different%20time%20periods%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22417%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20here's%20where%20things%20get%20a%20bit%20complicated.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20NBER's%20recession%20data%20between%20roughly%201850%20and%201950%20is%20somewhere%20between%20flawed%20and%20unusable%2C%20George%20Selgin%2C%20an%20economist%20and%20a%20senior%20fellow%20at%20the%20libertarian%20think%20tank%20the%20Cato%20Institute%2C%20told%20Business%20Insider.%20He%20said%20the%20NBER's%20pre-1914%20recession%20data%2C%20in%20particular%2C%20is%20%26quot%3Bvery%20poor%2C%26quot%3B%20and%20that%20only%20economic%20data%20collected%20after%20World%20War%20II%20is%20of%20good%20quality.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20example%2C%20while%20some%20efforts%20were%20made%20to%20track%20unemployment%20as%20early%20as%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2008%2F03%2F05%2Fbusiness%2F05leonhardt.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E1870s%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20Bureau%20of%20Labor%20Statistics%20didn't%20officially%20do%20so%20until%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bls.gov%2Fopub%2Fmlr%2F1948%2Farticle%2Fpdf%2Flabor-force-employment-and-unemployment-1929-39-estimating-methods.pdf%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E1929%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThis%20raises%20a%20series%20of%20questions%3A%20Are%20US%20recessions%2C%20in%20fact%2C%20much%20less%20common%20than%20they%20used%20to%20be%3F%20If%20so%2C%20who%20or%20what%20is%20responsible%20for%20this%20improvement%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20if%20not%2C%20what's%20gone%20wrong%3F%20After%20all%2C%20economists%20told%20BI%20that%20the%20US's%20diversifying%20economy%20and%20improving%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Eeconomic%20data%20should%20have%20made%20the%20US%20more%20resistant%20to%20recessions%20than%20perhaps%20ever%20before.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3ERecessions%20might%20not%20be%20less%20common%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20possible%20that%20NBER%20worked%20with%20subpar%20data%20but%20generally%20was%20able%20to%20identify%20when%20the%20US%20entered%20a%20recession.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20Selgin%20said%20alternative%20analyses%20of%20historical%20economic%20data%20have%20found%20that%20the%20US%20hasn't%20seen%20much%20of%20a%20decline%20in%20recession%20frequency%20over%20time.%20Selgin%20pointed%20to%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nber.org%2Fpapers%2Fw11157%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eresearch%20paper%3C%2Fa%3E%20published%20in%202005%20by%20Joseph%20H.%20Davis%2C%20now%20the%20global%20chief%20economist%20at%20Vanguard%2C%20as%20the%20%26quot%3Bmost%20reliable%26quot%3B%20source%20of%20recession%20data%20he's%20seen.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDavis's%20research%20put%20more%20emphasis%20on%20economic%20output%20and%20employment%20and%20less%20on%20prices%2C%20which%20can%20tell%20a%20misleading%20story%2C%20Selgin%20said.%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EFor%20example%2C%20while%20prices%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.investopedia.com%2Fask%2Fanswers%2F040715%2Fwere-there-any-periods-major-deflation-us-history.asp%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efell%3C%2Fa%3E%20during%20the%20late%201800s%2C%20this%20didn't%20mean%20there%20was%20necessarily%20a%20recession.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWhat%20Davis%20and%20other%20economic%20historians%20have%20shown%20is%20that%20much%20of%20the%20deflation%2C%20not%20all%20of%20it%20during%20those%20times%2C%20was%20driven%20by%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.loc.gov%2Fclassroom-materials%2Funited-states-history-primary-source-timeline%2Frise-of-industrial-america-1876-1900%2Fwork-in-late-19th-century%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eproductivity%20gains%3C%2Fa%3E.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221420%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Joseph%20Davis%20research%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F6630f3ab10dfcda40964c4c5%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221072%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ESome%20research%20has%20questioned%20the%20accuracy%20of%20the%20NBER's%20historical%20recession%20data.%3Cp%3EAn%20Improved%20Annual%20Chronology%20of%20US%20Business%20Cycles%20since%20the%201790s%20(Joseph%20H.%20Davis%2C%202005)%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EUltimately%2C%20Davis's%20research%20concluded%20that%20US%20recessions%20might%20not%20be%20as%20common%20historically%20as%20previously%20thought%20%E2%80%94%20casting%20doubt%20on%20the%20premise%20that%20recessions%20have%20become%20much%20less%20common%20over%20time.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20Davis's%20recession%20data%20only%20dates%20back%20to%20around%202000%2C%20Selgin%20said%20incorporating%20more%20recent%20data%20points%2C%20like%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-caused-the-great-recession%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EGreat%20Recession%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20would%20only%20reinforce%20the%20paper's%20findings.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20US%20economy%20is%20more%20resilient%20because%20it%20has%20diversified%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20some%20ways%2C%20the%20US%20economy%20is%20arguably%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newyorkfed.org%2Fresearch%2Fepr%2F02v08n1%2F0205kahn%2F0205kahn.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emore%20stable%3C%2Fa%3E%20than%20it%20was%20100%20years%20ago.%20Agriculture's%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pbs.org%2Fwgbh%2Famericanexperience%2Ffeatures%2Ftroublesome-farming-us%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edeclining%20share%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20economy%20is%20among%20the%20primary%20reasons.%20In%201935%2C%20there%20were%20about%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ers.usda.gov%2Fdata-products%2Fchart-gallery%2Fgallery%2Fchart-detail%2F%3FchartId%3D58268%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E6.8%20million%3C%2Fa%3E%20farms%20in%20the%20US%2C%20per%20the%20US%20Department%20of%20Agriculture.%20In%202023%2C%20there%20were%201.9%20million.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BA%20bad%20harvest%20for%20one%20or%20two%20crops%20or%20a%20drought%20season%2C%20that%20could%20give%20you%20a%20big%20downturn%2C%26quot%3B%20Selgin%20said.%20%26quot%3BThat%20doesn't%20happen%20in%20a%20diversified%20manufacturing%20economy%2C%20of%20course%2C%20where%20much%20of%20the%20GDP%20has%20nothing%20to%20do%20with%20the%20weather.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20ongoing%20transition%20from%20a%20manufacturing%20economy%20to%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fsponsored%2Fciti-2018%2Fthe-american-economy-is-experiencing-a-paradigm-shift%2F2008%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eservices-oriented%20one%3C%2Fa%3E%20could%20be%20making%20the%20US%20even%20more%20resilient%2C%20Satyam%20Panday%2C%20Chief%20US%20Economist%2C%20S%26amp%3BP%20Global%20Ratings%2C%20told%20Business%20Insider.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20most%20volatile%20is%20agriculture%2C%20then%20manufacturing%2C%20and%20services%20is%20the%20most%20stable%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said%20of%20economies%20with%20a%20particular%20industry%20focus.%20%26quot%3BSo%20the%20growing%20share%20of%20services%20also%20means%20you're%20going%20to%20have%20more%20stable%20economic%20growth.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAdditionally%2C%20Selgin%20said%20that%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ffred.stlouisfed.org%2Fseries%2FFYONGDA188S%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egrowing%3C%2Fa%3E%20US%20government%20spending%20relative%20to%20GDP%20over%20the%20past%20century%20could%20also%20be%20making%20the%20economy%20more%20stable.%20In%20part%2C%20that's%20because%20government%20spending%20doesn't%20tend%20to%20plummet%20during%20difficult%20economic%20periods.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBecoming%20more%20energy-independent%20may%20have%20helped%20as%20well.%20Before%202018%2C%20when%20the%20US%20exported%20more%20oil%20than%20it%20imported%20for%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.latimes.com%2Fbusiness%2Fla-fi-oil-exporter-opec-20181206-story.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efirst%20time%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%2075%20years%2C%20a%20huge%20spike%20in%20oil%20prices%20outside%20the%20US%20could%20seriously%20impact%20the%20economy%2C%20Panday%20said.%20Today%2C%20the%20US%20should%20be%20more%20insulated%20from%20such%20a%20price%20shock.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBut%20if%20recessions%20aren't%20much%20less%20common%20than%20they%20used%20to%20be%2C%20and%20the%20aforementioned%20developments%20should%20be%20making%20the%20economy%20more%20stable%2C%20where%20would%20the%20instability%20be%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Ecoming%20from%3F%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESelgin%20isn't%20sure%20what%20the%20explanation%20is%2C%20but%20he%20thinks%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Eit's%20possible%20that%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%2C%20which%20was%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fthe-us-federal-reserve-a-rich-history-of-financial-folly-2011-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efounded%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%201913%2C%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Ecould%20be%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Epartly%20responsible.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20Fed%20tends%20to%20overdo%20things%20sometimes%2C%20and%20others%2C%20it%20underdoes%20things%2C%20even%20though%2C%20in%20general%2C%20it's%20getting%20the%20directions%20right%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said%20of%20the%20central%20bank's%20interest%20rate%20policies.%20%26quot%3BThere's%20plenty%20of%20reason%20to%20not%20be%20complacent%20about%20the%20Fed's%20performance%2C%20to%20wonder%20whether%20it%20has%20really%20done%20what%20it%20set%20out%20to%20do%20when%20it%20was%20established.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Fed%20is%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fpersonal-finance%2Fwhat-is-the-federal-reserve%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etasked%3C%2Fa%3E%20with%20helping%20the%20economy%20maintain%20maximum%20employment%20and%20stable%20prices.%20Since%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ffederal-reserve-hikes-interest-rates-inflation-higher-costs-loans-mortgages-2022-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E2022%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Ethe%20Fed%20has%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fdid-fed-cut-interest-rates-march-meeting-continues-pause-inflation-2024-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eraised%20interest%20rates%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20an%20effort%20to%20bring%20down%20inflation%2C%20and%20it's%20pursuing%20the%20desired%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fjamie-dimon-soft-landing-outlook-recession-inflation-jpmorgan-geopolitics-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esoft%20landing%3C%2Fa%3E%26quot%3B%20of%20lower%20prices%20and%20a%20healthy%20labor%20market.%20Its%20policies%20may%20have%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fbusiness%2F2023%2F12%2F18%2Frecession-economy-inflation%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ehelped%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20US%20avoid%20a%20recession.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPanday%20said%20he%20believes%20that%20better%20economic%20data%20and%20the%20ability%20to%20%26quot%3Blearn%20from%20the%20mistakes%20of%20the%20past%26quot%3B%20have%20helped%20the%20Fed%20make%20better%20decisions.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EAvoiding%20recessions%20isn't%20the%20only%20indicator%20of%20a%20healthy%20economy%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20longer%20the%20US%20economy%20grows%20without%20a%20recession%2C%20the%20better%20it%20is%20for%20employment%20and%20Americans'%20standard%20of%20living%2C%20Panday%20said.%20But%20when%20it%20comes%20to%20measuring%20the%20stability%20of%20the%20US%20economy%2C%20measuring%20the%20frequency%20of%20recessions%20might%20not%20be%20the%20best%20approach.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEven%20when%20a%20recession%20technically%20comes%20to%20an%20end%2C%20and%20the%20US%20economy%20begins%20to%20grow%20again%2C%20that%20doesn't%20mean%20everything%20is%20fine%20and%20dandy.%20For%20example%2C%20the%20US%20exited%20a%20recession%20in%202009%2C%20but%20employment%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fgreat-recession-meet-the-terrible-recovery-2011-8%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edidn't%20return%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20pre-recession%20levels%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ffred.stlouisfed.org%2Fseries%2FCE16OV%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Euntil%202014%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIt's%20why%20economists%20should%20focus%20not%20only%20on%20the%20frequency%20of%20recessions%20but%20on%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fus-men-working-less-recessions-employment-productivity-2024-4%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epace%20of%20the%20economic%20recoveries%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20aftermath%2C%20Selgin%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EPanday%20said%20he%20thinks%20policymakers'%20response%20to%20the%20pandemic%20recession%20%E2%80%94%20which%20included%20trillions%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fstimulus-package-pandemic-surpass-great-recession-fiscal-plans-recovery-2021-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efederal%20COVID-19%20spending%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20shows%20that%20they%20may%20have%20learned%20the%20lesson%20from%20the%20sluggish%20recovery%20after%20the%20Great%20Recession.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20be%20sure%2C%20while%20a%20stable%20economy%20has%20its%20benefits%2C%20it's%20not%20the%20only%20indicator%20of%20a%20healthy%20economy.%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EFor%20example%2C%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3EAmericans'%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fbusiness%2Farchive%2F2016%2F02%2Famerica-in-1915%2F462360%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estandard%20of%20living%3C%2Fa%3E%20has%20improved%20considerably%20over%20the%20past%20century%20thanks%20in%20part%20to%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ffred.stlouisfed.org%2Fseries%2FA939RX0Q048SBEA%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egrowing%3C%2Fa%3E%20economy%20and%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fmost-important-inventions-of-last-30-years-internet-iphone-netflix-facebook-google-2019-5%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Etechnological%20progress%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20even%20though%20they've%20dealt%20with%20the%20occasional%20recession.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20years%20and%20decades%20ahead%2C%20any%20number%20of%20factors%20could%20plunge%20the%20US%20into%20a%20downturn.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20long%20economic%20expansion%20could%20raise%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmarkets.businessinsider.com%2Fnews%2Fstocks%2Ffed-rate-hikes-us-economy-recession-inflation-europe-jobs-market-2022-11%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Erisk%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20economy%20%26quot%3Brunning%20too%20hot%2C%26quot%3B%20Panday%20said%20%E2%80%94%20which%20could%20ultimately%20lay%20the%20groundwork%20for%20a%20recession%20if%20policymakers%20don't%20respond%20correctly.%20He%20added%20that%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.atlanticcouncil.org%2Fblogs%2Feconographics%2Ffinancialization-has-increased-economic-fragility%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Egrowth%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20the%20financial%20sector%20relative%20to%20the%20rest%20of%20the%20economy%20could%20pose%20risks%20if%20it's%20not%20properly%20regulated.%20And%20of%20course%2C%20unexpected%20global%20shocks%20to%20supply%20and%20demand%20%E2%80%94%20the%20pandemic%20being%20the%20most%20recent%20example%20%E2%80%94%20could%20wreak%20havoc.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20some%20Americans%2C%20the%20next%20recession%20might%20feel%20inevitable.%20But%20Panday%20said%20that%20isn't%20necessarily%20true.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BEconomic%20expansions%20don't%20die%20of%20old%20age%20just%20because%20of%20time%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%20%26quot%3BEven%20if%20it's%20been%20going%20on%20for%20a%20long%20time%2C%20it%20doesn't%20mean%20that%20you're%20going%20to%20get%20a%20recession.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EHave%20you%20changed%20your%20spending%20or%20savings%20strategies%20over%20the%20past%20few%20years%20because%20you%20feared%20a%20recession%20was%20on%20the%20horizon%3F%20If%20so%2C%20reach%20out%20to%20this%20reporter%20at%20%3C%2Fem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22mailto%3Ajzinkula%40businessinsider.com%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cu%3Ejzinkula%40businessinsider.com%3C%2Fu%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fa%3E%3Cem%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhen-will-next-recession-hit-us-healthy-economy-financial-security-2024-5%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1714989781000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F663260c710dfcda409655b1f%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhen-will-next-recession-hit-us-healthy-economy-financial-security-2024-5%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Data%20from%20NBER%20shows%20a%20promising%20trend%3A%20Recessions%20have%20become%20less%20common%20in%20the%20US.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22jzinkula%40insider.com%20(Jacob%20Zinkula%2CMadison%20Hoff)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A10%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fwhen-will-next-recession-hit-us-healthy-economy-financial-security-2024-5%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22A%2062-year-old%20employed%20'peak%20boomer'%20in%20California%20makes%20too%20much%20for%20affordable%20housing%20but%20lives%20in%20her%20car%3A%20'I'll%20work%20until%20I%20drop'%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%223072%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Cheryl%20Simmons%5C%