0has%20too%20much%20respect%20for%20the%2042-year-old%20legend.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A22%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Sterlite%20Power%20appoints%20Reshu%20Madan%20as%20CEO%20Global%20Products%20and%20Services%20Biz%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%22%2C%22published%22%3A1714987980000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fbsmedia.business-standard.com%2F_media%2Fbs%2Fimg%2Farticle%2F2024-05%2F06%2Fthumb%2Ffitandfill%2F400X400%2F1714987910-9392.jpg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Fcompanies%2Fnews%2Fsterlite-power-appoints-reshu-madan-as-ceo-global-products-services-business-124050600454_1.html%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Madan%20takes%20over%20the%20charge%20from%20Manish%20Agarwal%20who%20has%20decided%20to%20pursue%20an%20opportunity%20outside%20the%20company%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A0%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Fcompanies%2Fnews%2Fsterlite-power-appoints-reshu-madan-as-ceo-global-products-services-business-124050600454_1.html%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww-business--standard-com.cdn.ampproject.org%2Fc%2Fs%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Famp%2Fcompanies%2Fnews%2Fsterlite-power-appoints-reshu-madan-as-ceo-global-products-services-business-124050600454_1.html%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.business-standard.com%2Famp%2Fcompanies%2Fnews%2Fsterlite-power-appoints-reshu-madan-as-ceo-global-products-services-business-124050600454_1.html%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Why%20Is%20Cancer%20Called%20Cancer%3F%20Tracing%20The%20Origins%20Of%20The%20Word%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cp%3EOne%20of%20the%20earliest%20descriptions%20of%20someone%20with%20cancer%20comes%20from%20the%20fourth%20century%20BC.%20Satyrus%2C%20tyrant%20of%20the%20city%20of%20Heracleia%20on%20the%20Black%20Sea%2C%20developed%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.attalus.org%2Ftranslate%2Fmemnon1.html%232%5C%22%3Ecancer%3C%2Fa%3E%20between%20his%20groin%20and%20scrotum.%20As%20the%20cancer%20spread%2C%20Satyrus%20had%20ever%20greater%20pains.%20He%20was%20unable%20to%20sleep%20and%20had%20convulsions.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cdiv%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAdvanced%20cancers%20in%20that%20part%20of%20the%20body%20were%20regarded%20as%20inoperable%2C%20and%20there%20were%20no%20drugs%20strong%20enough%20to%20alleviate%20the%20agony.%20So%20doctors%20could%20do%20nothing.%20Eventually%2C%20the%20cancer%20took%20Satyrus'%20life%20at%20the%20age%20of%2065.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECancer%20was%20already%20well%20known%20in%20this%20period.%20A%20text%20written%20in%20the%20late%20fifth%20or%20early%20fourth%20century%20BC%2C%20called%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.loebclassics.com%2Fview%2FLCL538%2F2018%2Fvolume.xml%5C%22%3EDiseases%20of%20Women%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20described%20how%20breast%20cancer%20develops%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3Ehard%20growths%20form%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20out%20of%20them%20hidden%20cancers%20develop%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20pains%20shoot%20up%20from%20the%20patients'%20breasts%20to%20their%20throats%2C%20and%20around%20their%20shoulder%20blades%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20such%20patients%20become%20thin%20through%20their%20whole%20body%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20breathing%20decreases%2C%20the%20sense%20of%20smell%20is%20lost%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.loebclassics.com%2Fview%2FLCL477%2F1994%2Fvolume.xml%5C%22%3EOther%20medical%20works%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20this%20period%20describe%20different%20sorts%20of%20cancers.%20A%20woman%20from%20the%20Greek%20city%20of%20Abdera%20died%20from%20a%20cancer%20of%20the%20chest%3B%20a%20man%20with%20throat%20cancer%20survived%20after%20his%20doctor%20burned%20away%20the%20tumour.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3EWhere%20does%20the%20word%20%E2%80%98cancer'%20come%20from%3F%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20word%20cancer%20comes%20from%20the%20same%20era.%20In%20the%20late%20fifth%20and%20early%20fourth%20century%20BC%2C%20doctors%20were%20using%20the%20word%20%3Cem%3Ekarkinos%3C%2Fem%3E%20%E2%80%93%20the%20ancient%20Greek%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.perseus.tufts.edu%2Fhopper%2Ftext%3Fdoc%3DPerseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dkarki%2Fnos%5C%22%3Eword%3C%2Fa%3E%20for%20crab%20%E2%80%93%20to%20describe%20malignant%20tumours.%20Later%2C%20when%20Latin-speaking%20doctors%20described%20the%20same%20disease%2C%20they%20used%20the%20Latin%20word%20for%20crab%3A%20%3Cem%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.perseus.tufts.edu%2Fhopper%2Ftext%3Fdoc%3DPerseus%253Atext%253A1999.04.0059%253Aentry%253Dcancer1%5C%22%3Ecancer%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fem%3E.%20So%2C%20the%20name%20stuck.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EEven%20in%20ancient%20times%2C%20people%20wondered%20why%20doctors%20named%20the%20disease%20after%20an%20animal.%20One%20explanation%20was%20the%20crab%20is%20an%20aggressive%20animal%2C%20just%20as%20cancer%20can%20be%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdfg-viewer.de%2Fshow%3Fid%3D9%26tx_dlf%255Bid%255D%3Dhttp%253A%252F%252Fcmg.bbaw.de%252Fepubl%252Fonline%252Fmets%252Fcmg_11_01_03_03.xml%26tx_dlf%255Bpage%255D%3D248%5C%22%3Ean%20aggressive%20disease%3C%2Fa%3E%3B%20another%20explanation%20was%20the%20crab%20can%20grip%20one%20part%20of%20a%20person's%20body%20with%20its%20claws%20and%20be%20difficult%20to%20remove%2C%20just%20as%20cancer%20can%20be%20difficult%20to%20remove%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com.au%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DYYo-AAAAcAAJ%26pg%3DPA79%26dq%3DBut%2Bsome%2Bsay%2Bthat%2Bit%2Bis%2Bso%2Bcalled%2Bbecause%2Bit%2Badheres%2Bto%2Bany%2Bpart%2Bwhich%2Bit%2Bseizes%2Bupon%2Bin%2Ban%2Bobstinate%2Bmanner%2Blike%2Bthe%2Bcrab%26hl%3Den%26newbks%3D1%26newbks_redir%3D0%26sa%3DX%26ved%3D2ahUKEwi0qrq_9t6FAxUuSWwGHa1yB2IQ6AF6BAgKEAI%23v%3Donepage%26q%26f%3Dfalse%5C%22%3Eonce%20it%20has%20developed%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Others%20thought%20it%20was%20because%20of%20the%20appearance%20of%20the%20tumour.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20physician%20Galen%20(129-216%20AD)%20described%20breast%20cancer%20in%20his%20work%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.loebclassics.com%2Fview%2FLCL523%2F2016%2Fvolume.xml%5C%22%3EA%20Method%20of%20Medicine%20to%20Glaucon%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20and%20compared%20the%20form%20of%20the%20tumour%20to%20the%20form%20of%20a%20crab%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20have%20often%20seen%20in%20the%20breasts%20a%20tumour%20exactly%20like%20a%20crab.%20Just%20as%20that%20animal%20has%20feet%20on%20either%20side%20of%20its%20body%2C%20so%20too%20in%20this%20disease%20the%20veins%20of%20the%20unnatural%20swelling%20are%20stretched%20out%20on%20either%20side%2C%20creating%20a%20form%20similar%20to%20a%20crab.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3ENot%20everyone%20agreed%20what%20caused%20cancer%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20Greco-Roman%20period%2C%20there%20were%20different%20opinions%20about%20the%20cause%20of%20cancer.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EAccording%20to%20a%20widespread%20ancient%20medical%20theory%2C%20the%20body%20has%20four%20humours%3A%20blood%2C%20yellow%20bile%2C%20phlegm%20and%20black%20bile.%20These%20four%20humours%20need%20to%20be%20kept%20in%20a%20state%20of%20balance%2C%20otherwise%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jstor.org%2Fstable%2F10.1163%2Fj.ctt1w76vxr.21%3Fseq%3D1%5C%22%3Ea%20person%20becomes%20sick%3C%2Fa%3E.%20If%20a%20person%20suffered%20from%20an%20excess%20of%20black%20bile%2C%20it%20was%20thought%20this%20would%20eventually%20lead%20to%20cancer.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThe%20physician%20Erasistratus%2C%20who%20lived%20from%20around%20315%20to%20240%20BC%2C%20disagreed.%20However%2C%20so%20far%20as%20we%20know%2C%20he%20did%20not%20offer%20an%20alternative%20explanation.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3EHow%20was%20cancer%20treated%3F%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECancer%20was%20treated%20in%20a%20range%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fopac.kbr.be%2FLibrary%2Fdoc%2FSYRACUSE%2F17002971%2Fguerisons-du-corps-et-de-l-ame%3F_lg%3Dfr-BE%5C%22%3Edifferent%20ways%3C%2Fa%3E.%20It%20was%20thought%20that%20cancers%20in%20their%20early%20stages%20could%20be%20cured%20using%20medications.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EThese%20included%20drugs%20derived%20from%20plants%20(such%20as%20cucumber%2C%20narcissus%20bulb%2C%20castor%20bean%2C%20bitter%20vetch%2C%20cabbage)%3B%20animals%20(such%20as%20the%20ash%20of%20a%20crab)%3B%20and%20metals%20(such%20as%20arsenic).%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EGalen%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.loebclassics.com%2Fview%2FLCL518%2F2011%2Fvolume.xml%5C%22%3Eclaimed%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20by%20using%20this%20sort%20of%20medication%2C%20and%20repeatedly%20purging%20his%20patients%20with%20emetics%20or%20enemas%2C%20he%20was%20sometimes%20successful%20at%20making%20emerging%20cancers%20disappear.%20He%20said%20the%20same%20treatment%20sometimes%20prevented%20more%20advanced%20cancers%20from%20continuing%20to%20grow.%20However%2C%20he%20also%20said%20surgery%20is%20necessary%20if%20these%20medications%20do%20not%20work.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ESurgery%20was%20usually%20avoided%20as%20patients%20tended%20to%20die%20from%20blood%20loss.%20The%20most%20successful%20operations%20were%20on%20cancers%20of%20the%20tip%20of%20the%20breast.%20Leonidas%2C%20a%20physician%20who%20lived%20in%20the%20second%20and%20third%20century%20AD%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fbrill.com%2Fdisplay%2Ftitle%2F26579%3Flanguage%3Den%23%3A%257E%3Atext%3DSurgical%2520Instruments%2520in%2520Greek%2520and%2520Roman%2520Times%2C-Series%253A%26text%3DWith%2520The%2520Tools%2520of%2520Asclepius%2Cand%2520Roman%2520Times%2520(1907).%5C%22%3Edescribed%3C%2Fa%3E%20his%20method%2C%20which%20involved%20cauterising%20(burning)%3A%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EI%20usually%20operate%20in%20cases%20where%20the%20tumours%20do%20not%20extend%20into%20the%20chest%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20When%20the%20patient%20has%20been%20placed%20on%20her%20back%2C%20I%20incise%20the%20healthy%20area%20of%20the%20breast%20above%20the%20tumour%20and%20then%20cauterize%20the%20incision%20until%20scabs%20form%20and%20the%20bleeding%20is%20stanched.%20Then%20I%20incise%20again%2C%20marking%20out%20the%20area%20as%20I%20cut%20deeply%20into%20the%20breast%2C%20and%20again%20I%20cauterize.%20I%20do%20this%20%5Bincising%20and%20cauterizing%5D%20quite%20often%20%5B%E2%80%A6%5D%20This%20way%20the%20bleeding%20is%20not%20dangerous.%20After%20the%20excision%20is%20complete%20I%20again%20cauterize%20the%20entire%20area%20until%20it%20is%20dessicated.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fblockquote%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3ECancer%20was%20generally%20regarded%20as%20an%20incurable%20disease%2C%20and%20so%20it%20was%20feared.%20Some%20people%20with%20cancer%2C%20such%20as%20the%20poet%20Silius%20Italicus%20(26-102%20AD)%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.attalus.org%2Fold%2Fpliny3.html%5C%22%3Edied%20by%20suicide%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20end%20the%20torment.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EPatients%20would%20also%20pray%20to%20the%20gods%20for%20hope%20of%20a%20cure.%20An%20example%20of%20this%20is%20Innocentia%2C%20an%20aristocratic%20lady%20who%20lived%20in%20Carthage%20(in%20modern-day%20Tunisia)%20in%20the%20fifth%20century%20AD.%20She%20told%20her%20doctor%20divine%20intervention%20had%20cured%20her%20breast%20cancer%2C%20though%20her%20doctor%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newadvent.org%2Ffathers%2F120122.htm%5C%22%3Edid%20not%20believe%20her%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Ch2%3EFrom%20the%20past%20into%20the%20future%3C%2Fh2%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EWe%20began%20with%20Satyrus%2C%20a%20tyrant%20in%20the%20fourth%20century%20BC.%20In%20the%202%2C400%20years%20or%20so%20since%20then%2C%20much%20has%20changed%20in%20our%20knowledge%20of%20what%20causes%20cancer%2C%20how%20to%20prevent%20it%20and%20how%20to%20treat%20it.%20We%20also%20know%20there%20are%20more%20than%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cancer.org.au%2Fiheard%2Fis-there-a-cure-for-cancer%5C%22%3E200%20different%20types%3C%2Fa%3E%20of%20cancer.%20Some%20people's%20cancers%20are%20so%20successfully%20managed%2C%20they%20go%20on%20to%20live%20long%20lives.%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3EBut%20there%20is%20still%20no%20general%20%E2%80%9Ccure%20for%20cancer%E2%80%9D%2C%20a%20disease%20that%20about%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.who.int%2Fnews%2Fitem%2F01-02-2024-global-cancer-burden-growing--amidst-mounting-need-for-services%5C%22%3Eone%20in%20five%3C%2Fa%3E%20people%20develop%20in%20their%20lifetime.%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.who.int%2Fnews%2Fitem%2F01-02-2024-global-cancer-burden-growing--amidst-mounting-need-for-services%5C%22%3EIn%202022%20alone%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20there%20were%20about%2020%20million%20new%20cancer%20cases%20and%209.7%20million%20cancer%20deaths%20globally.%20We%20clearly%20have%20a%20long%20way%20to%20go.%3Cimg%20referrerpolicy%3D%5C%22no-referrer-when-downgrade%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcounter.theconversation.com%2Fcontent%2F228288%2Fcount.gif%3Fdistributor%3Drepublish-lightbox-basic%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22The%20Conversation%5C%22%20width%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3E%3Cspan%3E%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fprofiles%2Fkonstantine-panegyres-1528527%5C%22%3EKonstantine%20Panegyres%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20McKenzie%20Postdoctoral%20Fellow%2C%20Historical%20and%20Philosophical%20Studies%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Finstitutions%2Fthe-university-of-melbourne-722%5C%22%3EThe%20University%20of%20Melbourne%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fspan%3E%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3Cp%3E%3Cem%3EThis%20article%20is%20republished%20from%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%5C%22%3EThe%20Conversation%3C%2Fa%3E%20under%20a%20Creative%20Commons%20license.%20Read%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Ftheconversation.com%2Fwhy-is-cancer-called-cancer-we-need-to-go-back-to-greco-roman-times-for-the-answer-228288%5C%22%3Eoriginal%20article%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%5Cn%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ci%3E(Except%20for%20the%20headline%2C%20this%20story%20has%20not%20been%20edited%20by%20NDTV%20staff%20and%20